# External HTTP API port (POST /api/webhook). Tokens at ~/.config/nanoclaw/api-tokens.json.
EXTERNAL_API_PORT=3002
# Bind interface for the external API. Default 127.0.0.1 keeps bearer tokens
# off the LAN clear-text path. Set 0.0.0.0 (or a specific LAN IP) only when
# an external service like Home Assistant on a separate host needs to POST
# webhooks here. TLS still has to be terminated upstream — this server speaks
# plain HTTP.
EXTERNAL_API_HOST=127.0.0.1

# ── Host integrations (optional) ───────────────────────────────────────────────
# Set when this install uses the matching shim/CLI inside agent containers.
# `src/host-integrations.ts` reads these from .env at every spawn.

# Home Assistant REST API base URL (used by the `ha-api` shim). The HA
# long-lived token is held by OneCLI and injected by host-pattern matching
# at request time — register the secret in the OneCLI vault during cutover
# (`/init-onecli` + the migration guide cover the exact `onecli secrets
# create` invocation against running OneCLI). Verify HTTP-vs-HTTPS
# interception against your gateway version before relying on this.
# Leave unset to disable HA tooling for this install.
# HA_BASE_URL=http://homeassistant.local:8123

# Wolfram Alpha appid (used by the `wolfram-alpha` shim). Wolfram authenticates
# via a query-param appid; OneCLI's header-based injection doesn't cover this,
# so the value lives directly in the container env. Wolfram appids are
# rate-limited and low-value — clear-text in env is the documented trade-off.
# Leave unset to disable Wolfram tooling for this install.
# WOLFRAM_APP_ID=
